The paper discusses the impact of affect on cognitive processing activities and working performance of individuals, specifically in the context of software development tasks. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-category. Additionally, the paper proposes the use of psychology theory and measurements in SE research, indicating a potential fit for the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category. The paper also discusses challenges in conducting affect-related studies and proposes guidelines for conducting psychoempirical software engineering, which could fall under the Cybernetics (cs.CY), Programming Languages (cs.PL), and Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-categories.
